<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Creating PRM Objects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to create a new PRM object from points, triangles, and quads.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- START -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Starting a New PRM
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To create a new PRM object, click the <Bold>New</Bold> button, select
        <Bold>File → New</Bold>, or press <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>. This clears the current model and
        opens a blank editing space in the 3D viewport.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A PRM object is built from points and faces. Points are placed in 3D space, then groups of
        three points become triangles and groups of four points become quads. These faces form the
        visible surface of the object and can later be textured.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_create_new_prim.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- ADD POINT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Step 1: Add Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In the edit bar, change the current mode from <Bold>Select</Bold> to
        <Bold>Add Point</Bold>. In this mode, clicking inside the 3D viewport places a new point
        on the editing plane.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Points are the basic building blocks of PRM geometry. They do not form a visible surface by
        themselves, but they define the corners that faces will use.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_create_add_point_mode.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        For a first test, click four points anywhere on the plane. This gives you enough points to
        create either one quad or multiple triangles.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_create_points_in_viewport.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    You can hide or collapse the textures panel while placing points if you need more viewport space.
                    The texture panel becomes more important later when you start assigning materials.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- FACES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Step 2: Convert Points into Faces
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once points exist in the viewport, they can be grouped into faces. Faces are what actually
        become visible surfaces on the model.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Creating a Triangle
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Select <Bold>New Triangle</Bold>, then click three points in the viewport. The editor joins
        those points into one triangular face.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Creating a Quad
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Select <Bold>New Quad</Bold>, then click four points in the viewport. The editor joins
        those points into one quadrangular face.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_create_new_triangle_quad.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        After a triangle or quad is created, it is added to the corresponding face list under the
        Face Materials section. This list is important because individual faces are selected from
        here when you assign textures and UV regions.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_create_face_lists.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- WORKFLOW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Construction Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To build a simple PRM object from scratch:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a new PRM with <Bold>File → New</Bold> or <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Switch the edit mode to <Bold>Add Point</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click in the 3D viewport to place the points needed for the shape.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>New Triangle</Bold> to create triangular surfaces.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>New Quad</Bold> to create rectangular or four-sided surfaces.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the face lists to confirm the faces were created.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select each face and assign textures in the Texturing section.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the prim properties, such as collision type, shadow type, and object flags.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save the finished object as a PRM file.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PRACTICAL LIMITS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Modelling Notes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prim Editor is best suited for simple low-poly objects and small modifications to
        existing prims. It is not intended to replace a full modelling package. If your model needs
        detailed curves, complex proportions, or many small components, create the shape in Blender
        first and import it as OBJ.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The Urban Chaos engine can support up to roughly <Bold>5000 vertices</Bold> for a model, but
        that should be treated as an upper technical limit, not a recommended target. Most original
        prim objects are far smaller, often under 100 vertices. Keeping objects simple helps them
        render faster and keeps them closer to the original game style.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Very high vertex counts can cause performance issues. Use the 5000-vertex limit as a hard ceiling,
                    not as a normal modelling target.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
